rpetual Peace: Kant on the Legitimate Use of Political Violence -- t11: Military Intelligence: On Carl von Clausewitz’s Hermeneutics of Disturbance and Probability -- t12: Host Nations: Carl von Clausewitz and the New U.S. Army/Marine Corps Field Manual, FM 3-24, MCWP 3-33.5, Counterinsurgency -- tBibliography -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew essays exploring the relationship between warfare and Enlightenment thought both historically and in the present.Enlightened War investigates the multiple and complex interactions between warfare and Enlightenment thought. Although the Enlightenment is traditionally identified with the ideals of progress, eternal peace, reason, and self-determination, Enlightenment discourse unfolded during a period of prolonged European warfare from the Seven Years' War to the Napoleonic conquest of Europe. The essays in this volume explore the palpable influence of war on eighteenth-century thought and argue for an ideological affinity among war, Enlightenment thought, and its legacy. The essays are interdisciplinary, engaging with history, art history, philosophy, military theory, gender studies, and literature and with historical events and cultural contexts from the early Enlightenment through German Classicism and Romanticism. The volume enriches our understanding of warfare in the eighteenth century and shows how theories and practices of war impacted concepts of subjectivity, national identity, gender, and art. It also sheds light on the contemporary discussion of the legitimacy of violence by juxtaposing theories of war, concepts of revolution, and human rights discourses. Contributors: Johannes Birgfeld, David Colclasure, Sara Eigen Figal, Ute Frevert, Wolf Kittler, Elisabeth Krimmer, Waltraud Maierhofer, Arndt Niebisch, Felix Saure, Galili Shahar, Patricia Anne Simpson, Inge Stephan. Elisabeth Krimmer is Professor of German at the University of California, Davis, and Patricia Anne Simpson is Associate Professor of German Studies at Montana State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aEnlightenmentzGermany. 0aWar (Philosophy)xHistoryy18th century. 0aWar (Philosophy)xHistoryy19th century. 0aWar and literaturezGermany. 0aWar and societyzGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 0aWar and societyzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aWar in literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aEnlightenment thought.  agender studies.  ahuman rights discourses.  amilitary theory.  arevolution.  awarfare.1 aBirgfeld, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColclasure, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFigal, Sara Eigen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrevert, Ute, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKittler, Wolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrimmer, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrimmer, Elisabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMaierhofer, Waltraud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiebisch, Arndt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaure, Felix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShahar, Galili, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimpson, Patricia Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimpson, Patricia Anne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStephan, Inge, econtribut